<h2 id="toc2"><span><span style="text-decoration: underline;">COMMENTS:</span></span></h2>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Show&nbsp;Document-IRL</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[-]&nbsp;Hide&nbsp;Document-IRL</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><strong>SCP-1825:</strong> My first SCP that stuck. 1825 was kind of a favorite number for me, so I kinda made it a point that that number would be mine. I had the idea of a pinball SCP for a while, but I didn't know where to take it. I'd have to thank Scratskinner for the help on that.</p>
<p><strong>SCP-274:</strong> My highest rated SCP. Lots of work went into this in so many ways. Rhett helped me in making sure it was post worthy, and he was a big help on it. After some edits, it became what it is today. Will probably come back to it and organize it better soon.</p>
<p><strong>Finding The Machine:</strong> My highest rated article on here. Working on this was a complete joy. It was part of the 2013 New Year’s Contest, under the 'Unfounded' canon, and let me tell you: Working with those guys was a joy. Clef, Photosynthetic, and Pig_catapult were all just so helpful, and fun to work with. It was a great experience all around, and I thank them for that. Us winning was just the cherry on top.</p>
<p><strong>SCP-1294:</strong> I first posted this a while back, but it didn't go over so well. Not enough to go by… But then, like, a month after its deletion, I spontaneously said &quot;MAKE IT A FUNGUS&quot; while in the shower, and worked on it from there.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
Made more sense, and I got to go into squick, which was fun, but hard not to overdo. I even watched a video of a dead fox get eaten by a fungal colony so I could describe the Fennec Fox exposure log more vividly. Pretty cool stuff… However, I realized something, which I will go into on the next one.</p>
<p><strong>This Page:</strong> Well, one of my goals here was to work myself up enough to finally get one of these; not so much to describe my 'Nom de Plume', but to have a hub containing all the pages I've written, and an easily accessible link to my sandbox, and to give thanks to you all for writing. You guys are great, and you should feel great.<br />
&nbsp;<br />
Looking at my SCPs and my tales, I've noticed that my tales not only rank marginally better than my SCPs, I also had a bit more fun writing them… Though granted, I only had one tale up, but it seemed that way nonetheless. It was always the tone, and my need to operate in chronological order for me, and I hypothesized that if I wrote tales, that wouldn't be much of a problem. I decided to test this, and well… I was right.</p>
<p><strong>Capone:</strong> My favorite tale I've written. Finding the Machine was a great experience, but I think this trumps it in terms of content. I was truly inspired by <a href="/scp-1471">SCP-1471</a>. It was just a great SCP, so I just HAD to write something about it. I've always wanted to write a 'Heartwarming' article on here anyway, so I'm pretty happy that I got that goal completed as well. Also, SCP-1471-A's adorable.</p>
<p><strong>SCP-1903:</strong> An SCP I wrote after a long hiatus. I was originally working on a tale about Unlondon, but found that it wasn't really going anywhere, so I stopped. While writing the tale, I was going through my pictures, and saw Jackie. My first reaction? Write a story about it. I let some ideas germinate for a bit. I knew it was going to be a info-hazard, I knew it wasn't going to kill you, I knew it required the bestest story I could make up for it, and I knew it was just the beginning. My best SCP, and the first step of what I hope to make.</p>
<p><strong>SCP-1913:</strong> An SCP I wrote soon after with the idea of the Foundation seeing something that was actually chasing them. It worked with the time period, so I went with it. Scared people, and I think many people loved it.</p>
<p>This started the 30+ standard I have set for myself from here on out. For reference, this essentially means that if any article slips below 30 in the ratings, then I delete it myself. This only includes SCPs after, and including, Jackie (SCP-1903). I want my writings to be good. Period. The old stuff can stay, if only because I have a sort of attachment to them, but aside from that, if an article doesn't reach 30 within the week it's posted, and stay there, I'm taking it down to work on it more. If one falls behind in the rating, I'll give it a 24 hour grace period from when I noticed the rating drop.</p>
<p><strong>SCP-1619:</strong> No real comments. I wanted to further the story I've planned since membership, and I did.</p>
